00:00:21.327 --> 00:00:21.910
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:00:21.910 --> 00:00:22.785
So let's get started.

00:00:22.785 --> 00:00:24.340
So before I get into
any poker I want

00:00:24.340 --> 00:00:26.890
to talk about the
mentality I want everyone

00:00:26.890 --> 00:00:29.830
to try to have when analyzing
poker in this class.

00:00:29.830 --> 00:00:31.900
So I call it the
decision mentality.

00:00:31.900 --> 00:00:34.070
I'm going to start with a story.

00:00:34.070 --> 00:00:36.800
Who here has heard of
credit card roulette?

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:39.190
It's like a game you play
at the end of a guy going

00:00:39.190 --> 00:00:40.090
to restaurants.

00:00:40.090 --> 00:00:41.910
So what happens
is poker players,

00:00:41.910 --> 00:00:44.242
they're going to split
the bill by instead

00:00:44.242 --> 00:00:46.450
of everyone paying their
own bill, which is annoying.

00:00:46.450 --> 00:00:48.231
You have to keep track.

00:00:48.231 --> 00:00:50.480
You might have to Venmo
people after the exact amount.

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:52.810
And sometimes the
waiter or waitress

00:00:52.810 --> 00:00:55.040
doesn't want to split
the bill per person.

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:58.180
So poker players get around
this by just picking one person

00:00:58.180 --> 00:00:59.800
at random to pay the bill.

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:01.240
And we like making
this exciting.

00:01:01.240 --> 00:01:04.930
So what we do is we ask everyone
to put in their credit cards.

00:01:04.930 --> 00:01:08.060
And then we pull out the
credit cards one at a time.

00:01:08.060 --> 00:01:10.450
And if your credit card is
pulled out then you're safe.

00:01:10.450 --> 00:01:14.630
And the last person in has
to pay for the whole table.

00:01:14.630 --> 00:01:17.619
So it's a pretty fun game.

00:01:17.619 --> 00:01:18.910
Yeah, I think I'm pretty lucky.

00:01:18.910 --> 00:01:20.970
The biggest one I
lost was in Hong Kong.

00:01:20.970 --> 00:01:23.980
I once had to pay
around 1,200 USD.

00:01:23.980 --> 00:01:25.720
It was a pretty big table.

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:27.820
But overall I'm pretty
good at this game.

00:01:27.820 --> 00:01:29.180
It's a game of skill for sure.

00:01:33.090 --> 00:01:35.320
But sometimes this results
in some funny stories

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:36.820
with non poker players.

00:01:36.820 --> 00:01:39.860
So this is something that
happened to some poker players.

00:01:39.860 --> 00:01:43.600
So poker pro Matt, he goes to
dinner with poker pro Steven.

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:46.350
And that brings Emily, who's
a close friend whom he also

00:01:46.350 --> 00:01:47.980
has a romantic interest in.

00:01:47.980 --> 00:01:49.990
So when the bill
comes Matt's like OK,

00:01:49.990 --> 00:01:51.460
I'm going to pay for it Emily.

00:01:51.460 --> 00:01:52.960
So he puts in two credit cards.

00:01:52.960 --> 00:01:56.110
He's like the second credit card
is for Steven-- is for Emily.

00:01:56.110 --> 00:01:57.640
And then Steven
pays for himself.

00:01:57.640 --> 00:01:59.920
So Stephen puts in
one credit card.

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:01.900
So they play credit
card roulette.

00:02:01.900 --> 00:02:04.330
And then Matt, being
a very lucky guy,

00:02:04.330 --> 00:02:06.700
pulls out both of his credit
cards before Steven's.

00:02:06.700 --> 00:02:10.690
And Steven ends up paying
for all three of them.

00:02:10.690 --> 00:02:13.640
So now the question is,
who should Emily thank.

00:02:13.640 --> 00:02:16.900
So who would you thank if
you were in Emily's shoes?

00:02:20.090 --> 00:02:23.112
Does anyone want to
say to thank Steven?

00:02:23.112 --> 00:02:23.792
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:02:23.792 --> 00:02:26.000
PROFESSOR: Because Steven
actually paid for the meal.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.690
So I think it's a
totally reasonable thing

00:02:28.690 --> 00:02:31.440
to do as a reasonable person
to thank Steven who actually

00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:34.016
had to pull out his wallet.

00:02:34.016 --> 00:02:35.390
So in this class
we want everyone

00:02:35.390 --> 00:02:37.840
to think in terms of the
expected results and not

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:38.980
actual results.

00:02:38.980 --> 00:02:42.190
So Emily should be thanking
Matt because, on average, Matt

00:02:42.190 --> 00:02:43.540
put in the card for Emily.

00:02:43.540 --> 00:02:47.050
And on average Matt is
going to be paying for Emily

00:02:47.050 --> 00:02:48.450
because Matt's
going to be paying

00:02:48.450 --> 00:02:51.370
the one third of the time
that Emily would be paying.

00:02:51.370 --> 00:02:54.370
But at the time, Emily
thanked Steven for her meal

00:02:54.370 --> 00:02:56.670
and then didn't say
anything to Matt.

00:02:56.670 --> 00:02:59.180
And then Matt was upset about
it and told the entire poker

00:02:59.180 --> 00:02:59.680
community.

00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:01.346
That's how I found
out about this story.

00:03:03.490 --> 00:03:06.730
So we want to think about
in terms of on average

00:03:06.730 --> 00:03:09.570
what your decision
would have whether you

00:03:09.570 --> 00:03:12.430
would have made money in
expectation or on average.

00:03:12.430 --> 00:03:14.350
So roughly, the law
of large numbers

00:03:14.350 --> 00:03:16.680
says, over your
lifetime, the amount

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:18.970
you end up paying for
credit card roulette is

00:03:18.970 --> 00:03:21.310
the same as you would have
paid from splitting the bill.

00:03:21.310 --> 00:03:22.602
So you know why split the bill?

00:03:22.602 --> 00:03:24.309
You might as well just
save a lot of time

00:03:24.309 --> 00:03:26.280
by playing this fun
game every single time.

00:03:26.280 --> 00:03:27.900
And over your
lifetime, the amount

00:03:27.900 --> 00:03:30.280
you pay in credit card
roulette is roughly

00:03:30.280 --> 00:03:34.750
going to be what you would
have paid from splitting.

00:03:34.750 --> 00:03:37.120
So all randomness
eventually averages out

00:03:37.120 --> 00:03:38.560
to it's expected value.

00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:40.750
That's what this is saying.

00:03:40.750 --> 00:03:42.520
So what does eventually mean?

00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:45.434
So basically when we say
a gamble is very risky

00:03:45.434 --> 00:03:47.350
I'm not mathematically
defining anything here.

00:03:47.350 --> 00:03:50.350
But I just want to throw
out some intuitive concepts.

00:03:50.350 --> 00:03:52.450
So a risky gamble
is a gamble where

00:03:52.450 --> 00:03:56.470
it takes a long time to
converge at your expectation.

00:03:56.470 --> 00:03:59.630
But the point is, no matter
how risky it is, eventually

00:03:59.630 --> 00:04:01.060
it will get you.

00:04:01.060 --> 00:04:03.449
So there's a saying
that death, taxes

00:04:03.449 --> 00:04:05.240
are the two things that
eventually get you.

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:07.365
As poker players, we would
like to think that three

00:04:07.365 --> 00:04:08.660
things eventually get you.

00:04:08.660 --> 00:04:11.420
It's death, taxes, and
the law of large numbers

00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:14.260
will eventually-- you're going
to reach your [INAUDIBLE]..

00:04:16.820 --> 00:04:18.930
So here's another
hypothetical situation.

00:04:18.930 --> 00:04:21.310
So let's say you get off
at the wrong bus stop

00:04:21.310 --> 00:04:22.781
because you were distracted.

00:04:22.781 --> 00:04:24.280
And then you were
upset yourself you

00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:26.200
analyze how to not be
distracted in the future

00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:27.670
and get off at the
right bus stop.

00:04:27.670 --> 00:04:30.520
But then after you get
off at the wrong bus stop

00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:32.560
you find $1,000 on the ground.

00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:34.720
And then you immediately,
you're no longer upset

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:36.550
and you marvel at your riches.

00:04:36.550 --> 00:04:39.280
So this is sort of
an absurd story.

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:44.100
But situations like this
happen all the time in poker.

00:04:44.100 --> 00:04:45.640
You're going to
make a bad decision

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:49.720
but bad decisions still get a
good result 49% of the time.

00:04:49.720 --> 00:04:51.700
And if you make
the right decision

00:04:51.700 --> 00:04:54.830
you're still going to get a
bad result 49% of the time.

00:04:54.830 --> 00:04:58.420
So it's very important
to analyze your decisions

00:04:58.420 --> 00:05:02.780
without being biased by the
actual outcome that occurred.

00:05:02.780 --> 00:05:04.510
So you really want
to be obsessed

00:05:04.510 --> 00:05:08.140
with this self-improvement,
analyzing your decisions.

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:10.270
If you made $10,000
in a situation

00:05:10.270 --> 00:05:13.600
where you could have be $12,000
then that's not good enough.

00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:15.430
So I want everybody
to think in terms

00:05:15.430 --> 00:05:17.585
of what's the maximum
you could of made

00:05:17.585 --> 00:05:19.960
and analyzing what's the best
decision you could possibly

00:05:19.960 --> 00:05:22.010
have made in every situation.

00:05:22.010 --> 00:05:25.819
And sometimes it's hard because
if the result is exactly

00:05:25.819 --> 00:05:27.360
correlated with the
decision then you

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:28.830
can just go back and
look at the result

00:05:28.830 --> 00:05:30.900
and know whether you made
a good decision or not.

00:05:30.900 --> 00:05:33.210
But that's why learning
poker can sometimes

00:05:33.210 --> 00:05:36.570
be very, very hard because you
don't have immediate feedback.

00:05:36.570 --> 00:05:40.100
You're not sure whether
the decision you made

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:45.060
is what caused you to make that
money or you just got lucky.

00:05:45.060 --> 00:05:47.850
So with that being
said, now let's

00:05:47.850 --> 00:05:50.880
talk about some ways to
reason about poker hands.

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:55.380
So roughly there's three levels
of reasoning of poker hands.

00:05:55.380 --> 00:05:58.650
Level one my hand
versus your hand.

00:05:58.650 --> 00:06:02.640
But by this I mean, you can
see what your cards are.

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:05.070
And you look into
your opponents eyes

00:06:05.070 --> 00:06:09.210
and you say, OK, I can tell
your cards must be pocket kings

00:06:09.210 --> 00:06:10.050
or whatever.

00:06:10.050 --> 00:06:11.880
Your hand must beat
this other hand.

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:14.790
And you played your hand
exactly against your opponent's

00:06:14.790 --> 00:06:17.990
specific hand because you
have a soul read on them.

00:06:17.990 --> 00:06:21.570
So let's see the
example of this.

00:06:21.570 --> 00:06:24.360
So we'll watch an episode
of Poker After Dark here.

00:06:24.360 --> 00:06:26.695
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:06:26.695 --> 00:06:28.570
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:06:28.570 --> 00:06:42.478
- Raise to 1,200.

00:06:42.478 --> 00:06:44.933
- I think you would call
it this time, Patrick.

00:06:48.390 --> 00:06:49.930
- Button raises.

00:06:49.930 --> 00:06:50.854
Never anything.

00:06:50.854 --> 00:06:52.270
NARRATOR: Contrary
to what Patrick

00:06:52.270 --> 00:06:55.780
might think Jennifer has a real
hand and it just got better.

00:06:55.780 --> 00:06:57.340
She's flopped top set.

00:06:57.340 --> 00:07:00.390
Patrick flopped a pair of tens
with a gutshot straight draw.

00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:01.544
- I've got two pair.

00:07:39.313 --> 00:07:39.813
- Check.

00:07:53.188 --> 00:07:53.729
- Full house.

00:08:01.710 --> 00:08:03.906
- I can't beat that.

00:08:03.906 --> 00:08:05.510
- I thought you
had pocket kings.

00:08:10.052 --> 00:08:12.000
- I almost thought I had you.

00:08:16.383 --> 00:08:23.076
