00:08:23.076 --> 00:08:24.700
PROFESSOR: So yes,
this is sort of well

00:08:24.700 --> 00:08:26.926
known poker term from
way that in the day.

00:08:26.926 --> 00:08:28.300
If you're a Jennifer
Tilly hand--

00:08:28.300 --> 00:08:30.160
I'm sorry if I'm
making fun of her--

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:34.000
but basically she put her
opponent on a specific hand.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.039
She looked at
Patrick and Antonius

00:08:36.039 --> 00:08:37.539
and had a feeling
that he had pocket

00:08:37.539 --> 00:08:39.460
kings for some strange reason.

00:08:39.460 --> 00:08:42.720
And then what happened was,
so she had pocket jacks here,

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:44.220
which is a really,
really good hand.

00:08:44.220 --> 00:08:44.980
It's a full house.

00:08:44.980 --> 00:08:48.580
And she just checked the
turn and checked the river

00:08:48.580 --> 00:08:50.860
instead of trying to
get Patrick to put

00:08:50.860 --> 00:08:53.800
more money in because she
was so certain Patrick

00:08:53.800 --> 00:08:55.900
had pocket kings.

00:08:55.900 --> 00:08:57.640
Just mathematically
speaking, out of all

00:08:57.640 --> 00:09:00.040
the possible combinations
of cards you have,

00:09:00.040 --> 00:09:01.750
to put your opponent
specifically

00:09:01.750 --> 00:09:05.810
on pocket kings in this
example is basically unfounded.

00:09:05.810 --> 00:09:09.140
So this gets to
level two reasoning.

00:09:09.140 --> 00:09:11.590
So level two
reasoning is my hand

00:09:11.590 --> 00:09:14.560
versus your range of hands,
versus your probability

00:09:14.560 --> 00:09:15.940
distribution of hands.

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:18.730
And another name for this
is exploitative play.

00:09:18.730 --> 00:09:20.211
So let's look at
a different hand.

00:09:20.211 --> 00:09:21.835
And I'm going to show
you how to reason

00:09:21.835 --> 00:09:27.074
about this hand using level
two exploitative reasoning.

00:09:27.074 --> 00:09:28.990
So I'm not going to go
through the whole hand.

00:09:28.990 --> 00:09:31.960
But this is actually a real
hand I played in Macau five,

00:09:31.960 --> 00:09:32.890
six years ago.

00:09:32.890 --> 00:09:37.400
So we get to the river and I
had ace 10 in this situation.

00:09:37.400 --> 00:09:41.020
So the pot is 21,000 roughly.

00:09:41.020 --> 00:09:44.220
And my opponent
bets 8,000-- sorry,

00:09:44.220 --> 00:09:47.440
so the pot is 21,000 after
my opponent bets 8,000.

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:50.740
So basically the pot was
13,000 and my opponent

00:09:50.740 --> 00:09:52.939
bet 8,000 making it 21,000.

00:09:52.939 --> 00:09:55.480
And I have to decide whether to
call with a pretty good hand.

00:09:55.480 --> 00:09:56.680
I have a pair of aces here.

00:09:56.680 --> 00:09:59.290
But I know my opponent is
[? Rain ?] [? Kahn, ?] who is

00:09:59.290 --> 00:10:01.840
a very tight player and
doesn't really like bluffing.

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:04.600
So I don't think he's
really ever bluffing.

00:10:04.600 --> 00:10:07.480
If I'm beating him
here it's because he's

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:09.880
betting a hand that
he thinks is good

00:10:09.880 --> 00:10:14.320
but is actually worse than
mine, like ace eight basically.

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:18.106
So I model my opponent's range
as ace king through ace eight.

00:10:18.106 --> 00:10:19.980
I don't think he has
something even stronger,

00:10:19.980 --> 00:10:21.896
like pocket nines because
he would have raised

00:10:21.896 --> 00:10:25.870
more earlier in the hand.

00:10:25.870 --> 00:10:28.090
So let me run through
this calculation

00:10:28.090 --> 00:10:30.890
slowly for those of you seeing
pot odd for the first time.

00:10:30.890 --> 00:10:33.830
So here basically, I want
to think of it like this.

00:10:33.830 --> 00:10:39.370
The pot, which includes the
8,000 he just put out, is 21.

00:10:39.370 --> 00:10:43.257
We're considering calling for
8,000 so if we lose, if we call

00:10:43.257 --> 00:10:45.340
and her turns up ace king,
which is a better hand,

00:10:45.340 --> 00:10:49.090
then our net result from this
decision is negative $8,000.

00:10:49.090 --> 00:10:51.880
If we win and we get our 8,000
back as well as the 21,000

00:10:51.880 --> 00:10:56.470
in the pot, so we make,
our net is plus 21,000.

00:10:56.470 --> 00:10:59.110
So therefore, our
win to lose ratio

00:10:59.110 --> 00:11:01.720
needs to be at least
8,000 to 21,000 in order

00:11:01.720 --> 00:11:04.460
for calling to be
positive expectancy.

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:06.645
So we'll do the
exact calculation.

00:11:06.645 --> 00:11:08.020
I'll try to do it
somewhat slowly

00:11:08.020 --> 00:11:10.390
to show an example of how
to do this calculation.

00:11:10.390 --> 00:11:15.850
So essentially what I do
is I count the combinations

00:11:15.850 --> 00:11:17.550
of each hand that exists.

00:11:17.550 --> 00:11:21.490
So ace king, there's
eight combinations

00:11:21.490 --> 00:11:24.106
because there's two aces
remaining that I haven't seen

00:11:24.106 --> 00:11:25.480
and there's four
kings remaining.

00:11:25.480 --> 00:11:27.740
So it's two times four,
there's eight combinations.

00:11:27.740 --> 00:11:30.580
Same with ace queen,
ace jack, and ace eight.

00:11:30.580 --> 00:11:33.400
Ace 10 and ace nine, there's
only six combinations each

00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:35.780
because I have the
10, which makes

00:11:35.780 --> 00:11:38.140
him having ace 10 less likely.

00:11:38.140 --> 00:11:40.360
And for ace nine there's
a nine on the board.

00:11:40.360 --> 00:11:43.870
So ace nine is also
slightly less likely.

00:11:43.870 --> 00:11:45.640
So ace 10 we actually
get half the pot.

00:11:45.640 --> 00:11:49.930
So I'm just going
to roughly make

00:11:49.930 --> 00:11:52.480
that equivalent to us
winning three of those times

00:11:52.480 --> 00:11:54.230
and losing three of
those times, which

00:11:54.230 --> 00:11:56.600
is equivalent in expectation.

00:11:56.600 --> 00:11:58.880
So basically, if you
do this counting,

00:11:58.880 --> 00:12:01.750
there's 33 combinations
that beat us,

00:12:01.750 --> 00:12:03.850
there's 11 combinations
that we beat.

00:12:03.850 --> 00:12:07.155
And so our equity is
basically our probability

00:12:07.155 --> 00:12:09.280
of winning, which is
equivalently only the fraction

00:12:09.280 --> 00:12:11.380
of the pot that we own.

00:12:11.380 --> 00:12:14.110
So our equity in
this case is 25%.

00:12:14.110 --> 00:12:18.190
And the pot odds are 21 to 8.

00:12:18.190 --> 00:12:22.650
So we need we
basically 1 over 3.56.

00:12:22.650 --> 00:12:25.180
So 21 to 8 is 2.56 to 1.

00:12:25.180 --> 00:12:29.355
We need equity 1 over 3.56
to call, which is 28%,

00:12:29.355 --> 00:12:29.980
which we don't.

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:30.670
So I folded.

00:12:37.670 --> 00:12:40.205
So unfortunately, this
calculation is a bit ugly.

00:12:40.205 --> 00:12:41.330
You just have to do
it a bunch of times

00:12:41.330 --> 00:12:43.788
and convince yourself that are
doing the right calculation.

00:12:43.788 --> 00:12:46.610
Basically you got to remember to
add one when you're converting

00:12:46.610 --> 00:12:48.560
the odds ratio to an equity.

00:12:51.230 --> 00:12:54.410
So it should be
fairly simple math.

00:12:54.410 --> 00:12:56.870
So in this case,
I folded because I

00:12:56.870 --> 00:12:58.309
