00:24:19.890 --> 00:24:25.020
So put up your hand if you
want to join the contest.

00:24:25.020 --> 00:24:27.679
Put it nice and high so
that I can see if you

00:24:27.679 --> 00:24:28.720
want to join the content.

00:24:31.310 --> 00:24:32.495
So raise your hand high.

00:24:32.495 --> 00:24:33.050
It's OK.

00:24:33.050 --> 00:24:33.800
There's no embarrassment.

00:24:33.800 --> 00:24:35.420
The whole point of
poker is where--

00:24:35.420 --> 00:24:36.300
OK, cool.

00:24:36.300 --> 00:24:39.070
So now everyone open your eyes.

00:24:39.070 --> 00:24:40.680
So I think five people joined.

00:24:40.680 --> 00:24:42.120
So you guys come down here.

00:24:42.120 --> 00:24:45.270
Let's see who-- [LAUGHTER]
Let's see who won the pot.

00:24:45.270 --> 00:24:49.795
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:49.795 --> 00:24:50.670
PROFESSOR: That's OK.

00:24:50.670 --> 00:24:54.355
It's totally OK if you lost.

00:24:54.355 --> 00:24:55.480
So I think the four of you.

00:25:02.088 --> 00:25:03.102
Sorry, what's your name?

00:25:03.102 --> 00:25:03.810
AUDIENCE: Justin.

00:25:03.810 --> 00:25:04.060
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:25:04.060 --> 00:25:04.559
Justin.

00:25:04.559 --> 00:25:06.180
So I think Justin voted one.

00:25:06.180 --> 00:25:10.000
So good job Justin,
you would have made $3.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:10.681
All right.

00:25:10.681 --> 00:25:11.180
Cool.

00:25:11.180 --> 00:25:14.620
So what's the
point of this game?

00:25:14.620 --> 00:25:17.750
The point of this
game is so from a game

00:25:17.750 --> 00:25:20.444
theoretic point of
view no one really

00:25:20.444 --> 00:25:21.610
should be playing this game.

00:25:21.610 --> 00:25:26.830
So this is only known as the
k-beauty game from game theory.

00:25:26.830 --> 00:25:28.139
So how tall are you Justin?

00:25:28.139 --> 00:25:28.680
JUSTIN: 6'5".

00:25:28.680 --> 00:25:29.950
PROFESSOR: 6'5".

00:25:29.950 --> 00:25:31.649
So why did you play the game?

00:25:31.649 --> 00:25:33.940
Because he thought there's
probably someone who's going

00:25:33.940 --> 00:25:38.830
to be 6'2" who might
play the game, right?

00:25:38.830 --> 00:25:41.320
But if everyone knew that
if you're only 6'2" you

00:25:41.320 --> 00:25:43.611
shouldn't be playing this
game because someone might be

00:25:43.611 --> 00:25:46.630
6'5" then you wouldn't play the
game because someone else is

00:25:46.630 --> 00:25:48.850
only going to play the
game if they were like

00:25:48.850 --> 00:25:50.270
6'8" or something.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:54.490
So let's say we
played this again.

00:25:54.490 --> 00:25:57.730
Probably only Justin would play.

00:25:57.730 --> 00:26:00.310
Eventually this always
devolves into a situation

00:26:00.310 --> 00:26:02.180
where basically no
one is going to join.

00:26:02.180 --> 00:26:04.180
Because you know that no
matter-- even if you're

00:26:04.180 --> 00:26:06.580
like seven feet tall,
you're LeBron James,

00:26:06.580 --> 00:26:09.199
you would know that
someone would only

00:26:09.199 --> 00:26:11.740
played this game if they were
the tallest person in the world

00:26:11.740 --> 00:26:12.770
essentially.

00:26:12.770 --> 00:26:15.430
So basically poker
without blinds,

00:26:15.430 --> 00:26:17.710
which is the money
that's put into the pot

00:26:17.710 --> 00:26:20.260
at the start of every
hand, would essentially

00:26:20.260 --> 00:26:21.910
be like Who's Taller game.

00:26:21.910 --> 00:26:24.940
So when you play poker you want
the motivation of every hand

00:26:24.940 --> 00:26:26.590
to be stealing the
blinds, stealing

00:26:26.590 --> 00:26:28.780
the money that was
forced into the pot

00:26:28.780 --> 00:26:30.742
without the choice
of the person.

00:26:30.742 --> 00:26:32.200
So you would always
fold king king,

00:26:32.200 --> 00:26:34.450
which is the second best
hand in poker pre-flop,

00:26:34.450 --> 00:26:37.480
if there were no blinds.

00:26:37.480 --> 00:26:40.310
Suppose we were to play
Who's Taller again.

00:26:40.310 --> 00:26:43.720
But I told you that I'm going
to force Lee Marie to play.

00:26:43.720 --> 00:26:47.710
OK So now we've got
a game because now,

00:26:47.710 --> 00:26:50.770
even if you're not sure
whether you're the tallest

00:26:50.770 --> 00:26:54.334
person in the room, if
you're taller then Lee Marie

00:26:54.334 --> 00:26:55.750
then you have a
chance of winning.

00:26:55.750 --> 00:26:59.744
So that's essentially why we
need blinds to have a game.

00:27:05.470 --> 00:27:07.450
So you always want to
think how many chips you

00:27:07.450 --> 00:27:10.150
have in terms of the blinds.

00:27:10.150 --> 00:27:14.710
So having $400 in front of you
in a game where the blinds are

00:27:14.710 --> 00:27:17.890
$1 or $2, for our purposes,
is equivalent to having

00:27:17.890 --> 00:27:20.890
$4,000 in front of
you in a game where

00:27:20.890 --> 00:27:23.690
the blinds are $10 and $20.

00:27:23.690 --> 00:27:26.260
Because essentially,
everything you're wagering

00:27:26.260 --> 00:27:29.290
is relative to stealing
the blinds that were forced

00:27:29.290 --> 00:27:30.740
into the game at the beginning.

00:27:30.740 --> 00:27:32.620
So in both of
these situations we

00:27:32.620 --> 00:27:37.180
say that you have 200 bets,
or 200 big blinds, or 200 BB.

00:27:39.820 --> 00:27:42.580
So that's how to
calculate your stack size.

00:27:42.580 --> 00:27:45.400
But what's actually
important isn't stack size

00:27:45.400 --> 00:27:47.770
it's effective stack size.

00:27:47.770 --> 00:27:50.470
So effective stack
size takes into account

00:27:50.470 --> 00:27:54.730
the stack sizes of the people
remaining in the pot as well.

00:27:57.310 --> 00:27:59.330
So I'll give an example.

00:27:59.330 --> 00:28:03.400
So in this case, we're the
player with the ace jack.

00:28:03.400 --> 00:28:05.890
And we decided to go all in.

00:28:05.890 --> 00:28:10.390
So what is our exact stack size?

00:28:10.390 --> 00:28:14.320
The big blinds is 2,000,
the small blind is 1,000.

00:28:14.320 --> 00:28:17.800
And we wagered in total 42,000.

00:28:17.800 --> 00:28:20.485
So what's our stack size?

00:28:20.485 --> 00:28:22.360
AUDIENCE: 20--

00:28:22.360 --> 00:28:23.830
PROFESSOR: 21, right.

00:28:23.830 --> 00:28:24.995
It's around 21.

00:28:24.995 --> 00:28:26.740
It's around 21 big blinds.

00:28:26.740 --> 00:28:30.850
But we didn't really risk
21 big blinds here, did we?

00:28:30.850 --> 00:28:33.520
Can someone-- OK, I'll give
a $20 gift certificate.

00:28:33.520 --> 00:28:36.430
How much did we actually
risk in some sense.

00:28:36.430 --> 00:28:38.895
Yeah.

00:28:38.895 --> 00:28:40.270
AUDIENCE: I can't
see quite well,

00:28:40.270 --> 00:28:42.670
but I think 12 and
one half big blinds?

00:28:42.670 --> 00:28:43.900
PROFESSOR: Yeah, exactly.

00:28:43.900 --> 00:28:44.660
I'll remember it.

00:28:44.660 --> 00:28:46.630
I'll put it here.

00:28:46.630 --> 00:28:48.970
So we only risked 12
and a half big blinds

00:28:48.970 --> 00:28:52.450
because everyone in front
of us has already folded.

00:28:52.450 --> 00:28:55.210
And the true players behind the
small blind and the big blind,

00:28:55.210 --> 00:28:57.190
one of them only has 7
and a half big blinds

00:28:57.190 --> 00:28:59.470
and the other one only has
12 and a half big blinds.

00:28:59.470 --> 00:29:00.386
Can everyone see that?

00:29:00.386 --> 00:29:06.250
So even though UTG plus two
has 32 and a half big blinds

00:29:06.250 --> 00:29:08.320
could have
theoretically covered us

00:29:08.320 --> 00:29:10.810
and could have theoretically
taken all our money.

00:29:10.810 --> 00:29:13.060
But on this hand, because
they already folded,

00:29:13.060 --> 00:29:15.234
we're essentially only
risking at most 12

00:29:15.234 --> 00:29:16.150
and a half big blinds.

00:29:16.150 --> 00:29:17.417
That's the most we can lose.

00:29:17.417 --> 00:29:19.750
So we can't be eliminated
from the tournament this hand.

00:29:22.940 --> 00:29:24.980
So here's another example.

00:29:24.980 --> 00:29:27.192
So here you see
this guy that I'm

00:29:27.192 --> 00:29:28.650
going to call Low
Jack for now, you

00:29:28.650 --> 00:29:33.110
see him go all in
for 16 big blinds.

00:29:33.110 --> 00:29:35.590
So in this case, technically
he could lose all his money

00:29:35.590 --> 00:29:39.650
because we have more than 16
big blinds and we do cover him.

00:29:39.650 --> 00:29:43.930
But in reality, I'd say
he's probably not on average

00:29:43.930 --> 00:29:47.860
risking 16 big blinds because
most of the people who

00:29:47.860 --> 00:29:49.600
could call him,
other than us, have

00:29:49.600 --> 00:29:51.730
way less than 16 big blinds.

00:29:51.730 --> 00:29:53.350
Does that make sense?

00:29:53.350 --> 00:29:56.620
So essentially, there's
not like an exact formula

00:29:56.620 --> 00:29:58.180
for effective stack size.

00:29:58.180 --> 00:30:00.490
But you want to sort of
think of it in terms of you

00:30:00.490 --> 00:30:02.390
look at the stack
sizes of all the people

00:30:02.390 --> 00:30:04.690
who could potentially
play the hand against you.

00:30:04.690 --> 00:30:07.990
And you want to look at
roughly how much am I going

00:30:07.990 --> 00:30:09.510
to be risking in this hand.

00:30:12.114 --> 00:30:13.280
That's effective stack size.

00:30:13.280 --> 00:30:15.056
Does that make
sense to everyone?

00:30:17.652 --> 00:30:19.610
So the second thing I
want to talk about that's

00:30:19.610 --> 00:30:21.410
very important is position.

00:30:21.410 --> 00:30:24.260
So position is basically
where you are at the table

00:30:24.260 --> 00:30:25.610
relative to the blinds.

00:30:25.610 --> 00:30:27.200
So how many players
are remaining

00:30:27.200 --> 00:30:29.660
to compete versus
me for the blinds?

00:30:29.660 --> 00:30:31.430
Essentially, the
fewer players that

00:30:31.430 --> 00:30:35.340
are left the less strong my hand
needs to be attack the blinds.

00:30:35.340 --> 00:30:38.480
So I'm going to give
names for the positions.

00:30:38.480 --> 00:30:40.340
Basically the thing
that matters is how far

00:30:40.340 --> 00:30:41.720
you are from the button.

00:30:41.720 --> 00:30:44.030
So in this example
with ace jack,

00:30:44.030 --> 00:30:46.700
when everyone folded
to you and you're

00:30:46.700 --> 00:30:48.750
the dealer, which is
also known as the button,

00:30:48.750 --> 00:30:51.530
essentially to steal
the blinds, you just

00:30:51.530 --> 00:30:53.650
need to get through the
two blinds themselves.

00:30:53.650 --> 00:30:55.310
So that's essentially
two players.

00:30:55.310 --> 00:30:57.350
And then if you're in
one position earlier,

00:30:57.350 --> 00:30:59.240
when it was folded
to cut off, then he

00:30:59.240 --> 00:31:00.740
had to deal with three players.

00:31:00.740 --> 00:31:04.280
So you want to name everything
relative to the dealer

00:31:04.280 --> 00:31:05.580
essentially.

00:31:05.580 --> 00:31:08.150
So we can just quickly
go through the names.

00:31:08.150 --> 00:31:11.390
They'll get more
familiar as time goes on.

00:31:11.390 --> 00:31:14.920
So the first person to act,
we call them under the gun.

00:31:14.920 --> 00:31:17.720
So that's this guy here.

00:31:17.720 --> 00:31:19.070
And then we go around the table.

00:31:19.070 --> 00:31:22.060
It's under the gun plus
one, under the gun plus two.

00:31:22.060 --> 00:31:25.920
There can be different
names for the same position.

00:31:25.920 --> 00:31:30.620
So in this specific hand, where
there were only six players

00:31:30.620 --> 00:31:33.922
at the table, you could have
called Low Jack under the gun

00:31:33.922 --> 00:31:35.630
because under the gun
is the first person

00:31:35.630 --> 00:31:37.920
to act to the left
of the big blind.

00:31:37.920 --> 00:31:40.454
But essentially, it's
more clear to say Low Jack

00:31:40.454 --> 00:31:41.870
because when you
say under the gun

00:31:41.870 --> 00:31:44.540
you have to say under the
gun at a six-handed table.

00:31:44.540 --> 00:31:46.290
And then people will
know that means you

00:31:46.290 --> 00:31:47.720
got to get through five hands.

00:31:47.720 --> 00:31:49.770
But if you say Low
Jack it's very clear.

00:31:49.770 --> 00:31:51.380
You have to get
through five hands.

00:31:51.380 --> 00:31:55.700
So under the gun and then
plus two, and then Low Jack.

00:31:55.700 --> 00:31:59.030
You can also call under the gun
plus two, Low Jack minus one,

00:31:59.030 --> 00:31:59.840
if you want.

00:31:59.840 --> 00:32:03.322
And then High Jack,
cut off, button.

00:32:03.322 --> 00:32:05.030
Don't ask me where
these names came from.

00:32:05.030 --> 00:32:07.227
I actually have no idea.

00:32:07.227 --> 00:32:08.560
And then small blind, big blind.

00:32:11.520 --> 00:32:12.480
So that's position.

00:32:12.480 --> 00:32:15.990
And the importance of position
is basically the later

00:32:15.990 --> 00:32:18.404
you are the fewer hands
you got to get through

00:32:18.404 --> 00:32:20.820
to steal the button, to steal
the blinds of everyone who's

00:32:20.820 --> 00:32:23.280
already folded.

00:32:23.280 --> 00:32:26.400
So the third thing that matters
in a poker game is equity.

00:32:26.400 --> 00:32:29.100
So we talked about stack size,
we talked about position.

00:32:29.100 --> 00:32:31.320
The last thing is
actually your cards.

00:32:31.320 --> 00:32:34.840
So the equity of your cards is
basically your secret height

00:32:34.840 --> 00:32:35.970
for the Who's Taller game.

00:32:35.970 --> 00:32:37.345
So you can think
of it like that.

00:32:37.345 --> 00:32:38.970
Your cards is like
your secret height.

00:32:38.970 --> 00:32:41.310
And the probability of
you winning the pot,

00:32:41.310 --> 00:32:43.110
or equivalently, the
fraction of the pot

00:32:43.110 --> 00:32:45.150
you would win once the
remaining cards are dealt

00:32:45.150 --> 00:32:48.200
is called your equity.

00:32:48.200 --> 00:32:51.940
So I'm going to give some
examples of calculating equity.

00:32:51.940 --> 00:32:57.580
So here's an example where
we get it all on the turn.

00:32:57.580 --> 00:33:00.355
And so I have five four
states spades here.

00:33:00.355 --> 00:33:01.990
So I'm not in a great position.

00:33:01.990 --> 00:33:05.980
But let's count how
many outs I have.

00:33:05.980 --> 00:33:08.560
So this one I want to just
name a river card that

00:33:08.560 --> 00:33:10.417
would help me win the pot.

00:33:10.417 --> 00:33:11.500
AUDIENCE: Seven of spades.

00:33:11.500 --> 00:33:12.125
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:33:12.125 --> 00:33:13.250
AUDIENCE: Seven of spades.

00:33:13.250 --> 00:33:14.375
PROFESSOR: Seven of spades.

00:33:14.375 --> 00:33:17.170
So that gives me a straight
and a flush actually.

00:33:17.170 --> 00:33:18.710
So let's go along those lines.

00:33:18.710 --> 00:33:21.057
So how many spades are
there left in the deck?

00:33:21.057 --> 00:33:22.640
AUDIENCE: There
should be nine spades.

00:33:22.640 --> 00:33:23.889
PROFESSOR: Right, nine spades.

00:33:23.889 --> 00:33:28.160
And then how many cards help
me make a straight here?

00:33:28.160 --> 00:33:29.130
AUDIENCE: Six more.

00:33:29.130 --> 00:33:30.172
AUDIENCE: Seven or a two.

00:33:30.172 --> 00:33:30.880
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:32.000
A seven or a two.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:34.930
So it's six more because
there's eight sevens and twos.

00:33:34.930 --> 00:33:36.850
But I'm double counting
the seven of spades

00:33:36.850 --> 00:33:38.020
and the two of spades.

00:33:38.020 --> 00:33:40.540
So that's nine plus six.

00:33:40.540 --> 00:33:43.210
And then I actually have
to subtract one more card.

00:33:43.210 --> 00:33:44.650
Does anyone see what it is?

00:33:44.650 --> 00:33:45.150
Yeah.

00:33:45.150 --> 00:33:45.950
AUDIENCE: The queen of spades.

00:33:45.950 --> 00:33:46.350
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:33:46.350 --> 00:33:48.141
The queen of spades
because that's actually

00:33:48.141 --> 00:33:51.996
a disastrous situation because
then if it wasn't all in I

00:33:51.996 --> 00:33:54.120
would probably put more
money in the river thinking

00:33:54.120 --> 00:33:56.680
I have a flush and
lose to a full house.

00:33:56.680 --> 00:34:00.040
So it's 14 outs, 17 minus 3.

00:34:00.040 --> 00:34:02.350
Our equity is around 32%.

00:34:02.350 --> 00:34:05.740
It's 14 over the 44 cards
that could still come.

00:34:08.406 --> 00:34:09.739
Did that make sense to everyone?

00:34:09.739 --> 00:34:11.405
So that's one way of
calculating equity.

00:34:11.405 --> 00:34:14.050
It's just a very simple
probability distribution

00:34:14.050 --> 00:34:16.840
over the remaining cards in
the deck that could come.

00:34:16.840 --> 00:34:20.080
And if you're worried,
what if someone

00:34:20.080 --> 00:34:22.618
folded the queen of spades so
I shouldn't be counting that?

00:34:22.618 --> 00:34:24.159
Essentially, you
just want to pretend

00:34:24.159 --> 00:34:25.674
that the cards that
are in the muck,

00:34:25.674 --> 00:34:27.719
like the cards that were
folded by other players,

00:34:27.719 --> 00:34:30.324
they're essentially irrelevant
because they could have

00:34:30.324 --> 00:34:31.449
folded the queen of spades.

00:34:31.449 --> 00:34:34.260
But they could have also
folded an irrelevant card,

00:34:34.260 --> 00:34:35.860
like the jack of
hearts or something.

00:34:35.860 --> 00:34:38.290
So essentially you just
want to all the cards

00:34:38.290 --> 00:34:39.909
that you haven't
seen, it's easier

00:34:39.909 --> 00:34:43.254
to just assume that they
don't affect anything.

00:34:43.254 --> 00:34:44.670
In theory they
affect things a bit

00:34:44.670 --> 00:34:49.379
because if you know that the
dealer button folded two cards,

00:34:49.379 --> 00:34:50.920
even if you don't
know what they are,

00:34:50.920 --> 00:34:52.960
they're probably
more likely to be

00:34:52.960 --> 00:34:55.750
really crappy cards, like twos
and threes rather than aces

00:34:55.750 --> 00:34:57.958
because if they had an ace
they would have played it.

00:34:57.958 --> 00:34:59.950
But I think not worrying
about that is fine.

00:34:59.950 --> 00:35:02.980
You don't need to
worry about it.

00:35:02.980 --> 00:35:05.630
Another example of
equity calculation.

00:35:05.630 --> 00:35:07.880
So it's the exact same
example as before.

00:35:07.880 --> 00:35:10.060
But in this case, the
probability distribution

00:35:10.060 --> 00:35:11.530
isn't over cards
that could come.

00:35:11.530 --> 00:35:13.060
All the cards have already come.

00:35:13.060 --> 00:35:16.750
The probability distribution is
just over my opponent's hand.

00:35:16.750 --> 00:35:18.730
So this is the same calculation.

00:35:18.730 --> 00:35:21.970
We calculated our equity is 25%.

00:35:21.970 --> 00:35:24.040
And that's not a
probability distribution

00:35:24.040 --> 00:35:25.290
over cards to come.

00:35:25.290 --> 00:35:26.800
That's a probability
distribution

00:35:26.800 --> 00:35:30.610
over our beliefs of
our opponent's hand.

00:35:30.610 --> 00:35:32.290
So example three of
calculating equity.

00:35:32.290 --> 00:35:35.010
So this one you can't
really do by hand.

00:35:35.010 --> 00:35:38.280
Let's say you get it all in
pre-flop, with ace king suited

00:35:38.280 --> 00:35:39.750
against pocket twos.

00:35:39.750 --> 00:35:42.659
And you basically
need a calculator.

00:35:42.659 --> 00:35:44.700
There are certain websites
that help you do this.

00:35:44.700 --> 00:35:48.100
And ace king suited
against pocket twos,

00:35:48.100 --> 00:35:49.860
if they don't have
a two of your suit

00:35:49.860 --> 00:35:52.296
is actually a very small
favorite which is cool.

00:35:52.296 --> 00:35:53.670
But if you have
the two of hearts

00:35:53.670 --> 00:35:55.710
then you're actually
a slight underdog.

00:35:58.870 --> 00:36:02.000
So just make sure for
all the different things

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:03.420
equity could mean.

00:36:03.420 --> 00:36:06.570
Equity could mean a probability
over river cards, probability

00:36:06.570 --> 00:36:07.996
over the unknown.

00:36:07.996 --> 00:36:09.370
A very good
calculator in general

00:36:09.370 --> 00:36:11.370
is PokerStove,
which all have lots

00:36:11.370 --> 00:36:12.660
of examples of in my slides.

00:36:12.660 --> 00:36:16.720
And you can download
it via this link here.

00:36:16.720 --> 00:36:19.110
So this is an example
of using PokerStove.

00:36:19.110 --> 00:36:20.850
You can put in
exact calculations.

00:36:20.850 --> 00:36:24.090
Let's say you get it in with
two of diamonds, two of spades.

00:36:24.090 --> 00:36:28.162
So pocket twos on the flop of
5, 3, 2 versus a range where you

00:36:28.162 --> 00:36:30.120
know your opponent is
going to have a big pair,

00:36:30.120 --> 00:36:32.550
like pocket jacks plus,
you can actually run it

00:36:32.550 --> 00:36:35.790
and your equity is 85%, which
is actually surprisingly low,

00:36:35.790 --> 00:36:36.431
I think.

00:36:36.431 --> 00:36:38.430
Because it seems like
you've got three of a kind

00:36:38.430 --> 00:36:39.660
they've only got a pair.

00:36:39.660 --> 00:36:41.580
They have two chances
to hit one of two cards.

00:36:41.580 --> 00:36:43.840
But there's a lot of random
stuff that can happen,

00:36:43.840 --> 00:36:46.020
like if they have aces
they can make a straight,

00:36:46.020 --> 00:36:48.270
they can make a back
door flush, the board

00:36:48.270 --> 00:36:50.430
could come two more
fives, which counterfeits,

00:36:50.430 --> 00:36:52.590
or three of a kind deuces.

00:36:52.590 --> 00:36:56.280
So this is another example
of calculating equity.

00:36:56.280 --> 00:36:59.820
So this is just a summary of
the different situations you

00:36:59.820 --> 00:37:01.770
might want to calculate equity.

00:37:01.770 --> 00:37:03.530
And I recommend you
download PokerStove.

00:37:03.530 --> 00:37:06.430
But you don't really have to.

00:37:06.430 --> 00:37:08.520
And I guess one
question you could ask

00:37:08.520 --> 00:37:10.980
is how do you actually
do this at a table?

00:37:10.980 --> 00:37:13.320
So essentially, if you do
this a lot while you're

00:37:13.320 --> 00:37:14.880
studying about
hands and thinking

00:37:14.880 --> 00:37:16.540
about poker, eventually--

00:37:16.540 --> 00:37:19.050
I've been able to-- you just
memorize a lot of situations

00:37:19.050 --> 00:37:21.090
in general what the
probabilities are,

00:37:21.090 --> 00:37:25.260
or at least what the
correct decision is.

00:37:25.260 --> 00:37:30.840
So now let's talk about raising
two win the blinds and antes.

00:37:30.840 --> 00:37:34.350
So the antes, an ante
is an extra small bet

00:37:34.350 --> 00:37:37.680
that each player must put
into the pot each hand.

00:37:37.680 --> 00:37:40.560
And these sum to
around a big blind.

00:37:40.560 --> 00:37:43.070
And they come in during the
later stages of a tournament.

00:37:43.070 --> 00:37:44.725
And they're inexistant
in cash games.

00:37:47.250 --> 00:37:49.965
I stuck this under the rug
in the earlier examples.

00:37:53.710 --> 00:37:58.580
So in-- let me go
back-- so like in here.

00:37:58.580 --> 00:38:01.410
Do you see the
1,200 in the middle?

00:38:01.410 --> 00:38:03.150
So actually stuck
this under the rug.

00:38:03.150 --> 00:38:05.540
But that comes from
each player being

00:38:05.540 --> 00:38:09.570
forced to put in 200, which
is 1/10 of the big blind,

00:38:09.570 --> 00:38:11.110
at the start of every hand.

00:38:11.110 --> 00:38:13.980
And if you're playing
tournaments then

00:38:13.980 --> 00:38:15.990
this would usually be the case.

00:38:15.990 --> 00:38:17.850
Antes will come in fairly soon.

00:38:17.850 --> 00:38:20.529
If you're playing cash games,
where you just sit down

00:38:20.529 --> 00:38:22.320
and you can leave
whenever and you sit down

00:38:22.320 --> 00:38:25.110
and just play for
your own play money,

00:38:25.110 --> 00:38:27.790
then there's usually no antes.

00:38:27.790 --> 00:38:29.867
But antes actually make
a world of difference

00:38:29.867 --> 00:38:31.200
in terms of what you want to do.

00:38:34.290 --> 00:38:38.100
It's not just the stakes are
bigger when there's antes

00:38:38.100 --> 00:38:39.780
because you don't
want to just think

00:38:39.780 --> 00:38:42.390
of it like there's extra
money in the pot every hand.

00:38:42.390 --> 00:38:44.370
It's equivalent to the
blinds being bigger.

00:38:44.370 --> 00:38:47.910
That's not true because you
also have to put in an ante.

00:38:47.910 --> 00:38:50.520
So if the blinds were
proportionally bigger

00:38:50.520 --> 00:38:53.790
to cover the antes you would
have to raise to a bigger size

00:38:53.790 --> 00:38:55.620
to try to steal the blinds.

00:38:55.620 --> 00:38:58.500
But with antes you don't need
to raise to any bigger size

00:38:58.500 --> 00:38:59.630
to try to steal the blinds.

00:38:59.630 --> 00:39:01.530
So it's actually
very action driving.

00:39:01.530 --> 00:39:02.424
It's very exciting.

00:39:02.424 --> 00:39:03.840
It makes it so
that your basically

00:39:03.840 --> 00:39:06.930
want to play a very
wide range of hands.

00:39:06.930 --> 00:39:08.910
And you really just
want to be trying

00:39:08.910 --> 00:39:12.720
to win the blinds as often as
possible because winning one

00:39:12.720 --> 00:39:16.440
pot with the antes is so big.

00:39:16.440 --> 00:39:19.690
So this is what it looks like.

00:39:19.690 --> 00:39:21.240
So the first thing
I'm going to say

00:39:21.240 --> 00:39:23.531
is if you're going to start
playing tournaments tonight

00:39:23.531 --> 00:39:26.679
is if no one has raised yet you
really, you don't want to call.

00:39:26.679 --> 00:39:28.220
You want it to raise
to give yourself

00:39:28.220 --> 00:39:30.630
a chance of winning the
blinds without seeing a flop.

00:39:30.630 --> 00:39:32.970
So I'd say the most
common beginner mistake

00:39:32.970 --> 00:39:37.260
I see beginner poker
players make is not raising

00:39:37.260 --> 00:39:39.940
when no one has raised before.

00:39:39.940 --> 00:39:43.740
So in this case, it would
be just calling for 2,000

00:39:43.740 --> 00:39:44.970
and trying to see a flop.

00:39:44.970 --> 00:39:46.890
But the main issue
is you're giving

00:39:46.890 --> 00:39:49.380
the big blind they
can just check and see

00:39:49.380 --> 00:39:50.490
the flop for free.

00:39:50.490 --> 00:39:52.640
Whereas if you raise you
put them to a decision.

00:39:52.640 --> 00:39:53.940
And they might fold,
and you might just

00:39:53.940 --> 00:39:55.480
win the pot for
free without having

00:39:55.480 --> 00:39:58.230
to do anything essentially.

00:39:58.230 --> 00:40:01.380
So how much do you
raise when I say raise.

00:40:01.380 --> 00:40:02.910
The minimum raise
size you can do

00:40:02.910 --> 00:40:05.440
is raising to two big blinds.

00:40:05.440 --> 00:40:07.470
However, this is a
bit small because you

00:40:07.470 --> 00:40:10.950
give the blinds fairly good
odds to make a profitable call.

00:40:10.950 --> 00:40:13.890
Although, it's
not even that bad.

00:40:13.890 --> 00:40:16.140
So let me just talk in
general about raising

00:40:16.140 --> 00:40:17.760
big versus raising small.

00:40:17.760 --> 00:40:20.190
So the advantage
of raising small

00:40:20.190 --> 00:40:21.900
is that you're risking less.

00:40:21.900 --> 00:40:24.530
Like let's say you raise and
then the next person re-raises,

00:40:24.530 --> 00:40:26.490
and then the next
person goes all in.

00:40:26.490 --> 00:40:29.870
So you know probably those two
people have pretty good hands

00:40:29.870 --> 00:40:30.960
and you want to fold.

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:33.340
If you raise to a small
size then you can fold

00:40:33.340 --> 00:40:35.070
and you don't lose that much.

00:40:35.070 --> 00:40:39.040
If I raise to five big blinds
then I'm losing a lot more.

00:40:39.040 --> 00:40:41.190
But what's the
benefit of raising big

00:40:41.190 --> 00:40:44.490
is you give other people
worse odds to call.

00:40:44.490 --> 00:40:46.272
If I only raise
to two big blinds,

00:40:46.272 --> 00:40:47.730
let's actually do
this calculation.

00:40:47.730 --> 00:40:50.040
Let's say here, instead
of going all in I

00:40:50.040 --> 00:40:53.360
raise two big blinds,
which is 4,000.

00:40:53.360 --> 00:40:54.990
What odds am I
essentially giving

00:40:54.990 --> 00:40:57.330
the big blind you call to call?

00:41:00.930 --> 00:41:03.210
So this is actually, in
this very exact situation,

00:41:03.210 --> 00:41:05.910
this is a very common
mistake I see beginners make,

00:41:05.910 --> 00:41:09.100
which is you raise
to only 4,000.

00:41:09.100 --> 00:41:09.880
Yeah.

00:41:09.880 --> 00:41:12.450
AUDIENCE: So there's
8,000 that's in the pot

00:41:12.450 --> 00:41:14.152
and they have to call
2,000, so it's 21?

00:41:14.152 --> 00:41:14.860
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:41:14.860 --> 00:41:15.419
So it's 41.

00:41:15.419 --> 00:41:16.710
But there's also a small blind.

00:41:16.710 --> 00:41:20.050
So there's actually going to be
9,000 essentially in the pot.

00:41:20.050 --> 00:41:20.880
Yeah.

00:41:20.880 --> 00:41:22.200
So it's going to be 8,800 in.

00:41:22.200 --> 00:41:23.158
It's going to be 8,800.

00:41:23.158 --> 00:41:24.990
So approximately 9,000.

00:41:24.990 --> 00:41:27.285
And they only have to
call 2,000 to see the pot.

00:41:27.285 --> 00:41:30.190
Does that make
sense to everyone?

00:41:30.190 --> 00:41:32.910
So the odds are
actually 4.5 to 1.

00:41:32.910 --> 00:41:35.530
And ace jack off-suit
is a great hand.

00:41:35.530 --> 00:41:38.820
But there's no
hand that ace jack

00:41:38.820 --> 00:41:43.680
off-suit is more than a
4.5 to 1 favorite against.

00:41:43.680 --> 00:41:46.920
So in some sense, basically,
even if they have jacks two,

00:41:46.920 --> 00:41:50.880
or whatever, ace two, think
of the best possible case,

00:41:50.880 --> 00:41:53.110
you're still not doing
better than the odds

00:41:53.110 --> 00:41:53.955
you're giving them.

00:41:57.360 --> 00:42:00.590
So on the other hand
though, it is really risky

00:42:00.590 --> 00:42:01.990
to raise more than 2.25.

00:42:01.990 --> 00:42:04.826
So a reasonable rule
of thumb, I'd say,

00:42:04.826 --> 00:42:08.209
is to raise to the 2.25
big blinds in tournaments.

00:42:08.209 --> 00:42:09.500
I know it's pretty close to do.

00:42:09.500 --> 00:42:12.680
If you just raised to two
it's probably not that bad.

00:42:12.680 --> 00:42:14.210
But roughly speaking,
I think this

00:42:14.210 --> 00:42:16.310
is a reasonable rule of thumb.

00:42:16.310 --> 00:42:18.080
Earlier you could
try to raise to more.

00:42:18.080 --> 00:42:19.640
I think that's
sort of customary,

00:42:19.640 --> 00:42:23.210
although I don't think
it's theoretically optimal.

00:42:23.210 --> 00:42:25.030
You'll often see
players raise to like

00:42:25.030 --> 00:42:28.000
three blinds, especially
when you watch pro players.

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:29.120
They'll raise to bigger.

00:42:29.120 --> 00:42:30.800
But the main reason
is because they're

00:42:30.800 --> 00:42:32.720
the better player by
a lot and they're just

00:42:32.720 --> 00:42:35.660
trying to make big pots,
which is reasonable.

00:42:35.660 --> 00:42:38.370
If you're trying to
just play big pots

00:42:38.370 --> 00:42:41.270
and win big pots then raising
to the bigger size is fine.

00:42:41.270 --> 00:42:43.490
But I don't think there's
any theoretical reason

00:42:43.490 --> 00:42:49.340
to raise to more than 2.25
big blinds in most situations.

00:42:49.340 --> 00:42:53.600
Other than when in cash
games, where all players have

00:42:53.600 --> 00:42:55.340
a lot of money, then
it's a bit different

00:42:55.340 --> 00:42:56.714
because also in
cash games you're

00:42:56.714 --> 00:42:59.930
not worried about risking
more because you're not

00:42:59.930 --> 00:43:03.710
worried about losing
out of the tournament.

00:43:03.710 --> 00:43:07.520
So the other thing is instead
of raising you should just

00:43:07.520 --> 00:43:12.830
go all in if the effective stack
size is 12 big blinds or less.

00:43:12.830 --> 00:43:15.365
So recall, the rational
for raising big

00:43:15.365 --> 00:43:17.510
is to prevent others
from calling for cheap.

00:43:17.510 --> 00:43:19.130
But the rational
for raising small

00:43:19.130 --> 00:43:21.830
is to lose less if we get
re-raised and have to fold.

00:43:21.830 --> 00:43:24.950
But 12 big blinds is sort of the
point where it's small enough

00:43:24.950 --> 00:43:27.500
that you never really want
to fold after committing

00:43:27.500 --> 00:43:29.180
2.25 big blinds.

00:43:29.180 --> 00:43:32.430
So if I only have 12 big
blinds, I raise 2.25,

00:43:32.430 --> 00:43:36.660
I've only got 9.75 left after.

00:43:36.660 --> 00:43:39.440
OK, fine, if I get raises and
re-raised maybe I'll fold.

00:43:39.440 --> 00:43:42.080
But even if I get
re-raised once,

00:43:42.080 --> 00:43:44.120
if I'm raising in
the first place

00:43:44.120 --> 00:43:46.850
my hand is going
to be reasonable.

00:43:46.850 --> 00:43:48.320
If it's a Who's
Taller game I'm not

00:43:48.320 --> 00:43:50.270
going to raise in
the first place

00:43:50.270 --> 00:43:52.760
if I'm 5 feet, or something.

00:43:52.760 --> 00:43:56.360
So your hand will be reasonable.

00:43:56.360 --> 00:44:00.260
So this is beginner mistake
number two is being too scared

00:44:00.260 --> 00:44:01.310
to go all in pre-flop.

00:44:01.310 --> 00:44:05.240
So that's why this ace jack
hand, I actually cheated a bit.

00:44:05.240 --> 00:44:08.030
So technically here, the
effective stack size is--

00:44:08.030 --> 00:44:11.420
the big blind has 12
and a half big blinds

00:44:11.420 --> 00:44:13.550
but the small one
only has 7 and a half.

00:44:13.550 --> 00:44:17.930
So I roughly said, the effective
stack size is less than 12,

00:44:17.930 --> 00:44:19.864
and I just went all in.

00:44:19.864 --> 00:44:21.780
So that's definitely a
beginner mistake number

00:44:21.780 --> 00:44:27.920
two in tournaments is to be too
scared to go all in pre-flop.

00:44:27.920 --> 00:44:31.370
So what your goal essentially
should be-- oh, sorry.

00:44:31.370 --> 00:44:33.680
I should say the rule is--

00:44:33.680 --> 00:44:36.350
so all of the numbers I
said assume there's antes.

00:44:36.350 --> 00:44:39.140
If there's no antes you should
change to 10 big blinds.

00:44:39.140 --> 00:44:41.180
So the threshold
for going all in

00:44:41.180 --> 00:44:43.807
should be less because
when there's no antes

00:44:43.807 --> 00:44:46.098
you want to be risking less
because the pot is smaller.

00:44:49.110 --> 00:44:52.200
So overall, when I
talked about position

00:44:52.200 --> 00:44:53.975
I talked about stack size.

00:44:53.975 --> 00:44:56.100
Essentially what I'm trying
to get the point across

00:44:56.100 --> 00:44:58.770
is if you're just
starting out, players

00:44:58.770 --> 00:45:01.230
tend to make all decisions
based on their cards.

00:45:01.230 --> 00:45:03.390
It's just like, I
have a pair of jacks.

00:45:03.390 --> 00:45:04.980
I see my pair of
jacks on this board.

00:45:04.980 --> 00:45:06.540
I have a pair
that's pretty good.

00:45:06.540 --> 00:45:09.900
And you sort of tend to ignore
what the effect of stack size

00:45:09.900 --> 00:45:12.370
is, how much you're
wagering, and position.

00:45:12.370 --> 00:45:14.460
But experienced
players, the cards

00:45:14.460 --> 00:45:16.530
actually matter much,
much less to the.

00:45:16.530 --> 00:45:19.590
In fact, if you're
doing optimal play

00:45:19.590 --> 00:45:21.720
you don't care in some
sense what your cards are.

00:45:21.720 --> 00:45:25.990
You just care what your range
of cards are at that point.

00:45:25.990 --> 00:45:28.620
So experienced players, they're
willing to raise the blinds

00:45:28.620 --> 00:45:31.890
with much weaker hands
from good positions rather

00:45:31.890 --> 00:45:32.847
than early positions.

00:45:32.847 --> 00:45:34.680
And they're going to
risk going all in a lot

00:45:34.680 --> 00:45:36.390
more frequently with
a lot worse hands

00:45:36.390 --> 00:45:37.744
if their stack size is low.

00:45:37.744 --> 00:45:39.160
So I want you to
think about that.

00:45:39.160 --> 00:45:41.400
So if you're just
starting out that's fine.

00:45:41.400 --> 00:45:43.140
If you're still
trying to figure out

00:45:43.140 --> 00:45:45.280
whether you have a straight and
stuff like that, that's fine.

00:45:45.280 --> 00:45:46.950
And it's totally fine
if you try to play

00:45:46.950 --> 00:45:48.270
based just on your cards.

00:45:48.270 --> 00:45:50.550
But I want everyone's goal
by the end of the class

00:45:50.550 --> 00:45:53.700
to be able to play based
on these other factors

00:45:53.700 --> 00:45:56.322
more so than your cards.

00:45:56.322 --> 00:45:58.030
So that being said,
I'm going to give you

00:45:58.030 --> 00:46:01.150
some concrete suggestions
for those of you

00:46:01.150 --> 00:46:03.530
who might want to start
playing tonight of what hands

00:46:03.530 --> 00:46:07.830
you should be playing
from each position.

00:46:07.830 --> 00:46:12.240
So most of the tournaments will
have nine players per table.

00:46:12.240 --> 00:46:15.610
So this is going to be roughly
a range I recommend to open.

00:46:15.610 --> 00:46:17.080
So these are the
range of hands you

00:46:17.080 --> 00:46:20.450
should be playing from
the worst position,

00:46:20.450 --> 00:46:22.220
so under the gun at
a nine-handed table.

00:46:22.220 --> 00:46:24.050
So there's eight
players left behind you.

00:46:24.050 --> 00:46:25.540
You can pick up
really good hands.

00:46:25.540 --> 00:46:29.070
So it's aces, kings, queens,
jacks; ace king off-suited;

00:46:29.070 --> 00:46:33.720
ace king off-suit; 10s; ace
queen suited; ace queen off.

00:46:33.720 --> 00:46:35.950
So that's basically
the list of hands.

00:46:35.950 --> 00:46:38.230
These are only premium hands.

00:46:38.230 --> 00:46:41.580
This is like 6.2%
of hands, I think.

00:46:41.580 --> 00:46:43.370
It's a very premium range.

00:46:43.370 --> 00:46:45.460
So note how tight this is.

00:46:48.400 --> 00:46:50.680
Because the thing to
remember is only the best

00:46:50.680 --> 00:46:53.980
hand out of nine hands at the
table is going to get the pot.

00:46:53.980 --> 00:46:56.980
When there's nine hands, even
though the average hand is

00:46:56.980 --> 00:46:59.224
really bad the best
hand out of nine hands

00:46:59.224 --> 00:47:00.640
is always going
to be pretty good.

00:47:00.640 --> 00:47:02.880
So to even think that you have
a chance you need to start out

00:47:02.880 --> 00:47:04.250
with a very premium hold 'em.

00:47:07.840 --> 00:47:10.780
Roughly, what do you add
as you go around the table?

00:47:10.780 --> 00:47:12.077
So for the second position--

00:47:12.077 --> 00:47:14.410
I'm going to post all these
slides before the tournament

00:47:14.410 --> 00:47:15.201
starts, by the way.

00:47:15.201 --> 00:47:17.020
So you don't feel
that you scramble

00:47:17.020 --> 00:47:18.850
to write all this down.

00:47:18.850 --> 00:47:21.790
I'm going to post it.

00:47:21.790 --> 00:47:25.510
From the second position,
I put in black the hands

00:47:25.510 --> 00:47:27.550
that I would open from
the previous position.

00:47:27.550 --> 00:47:29.770
And I've put in red the
hands that I would open

00:47:29.770 --> 00:47:31.810
from that position in addition.

00:47:31.810 --> 00:47:33.740
So second position
there's one less player.

00:47:33.740 --> 00:47:34.240
OK.

00:47:34.240 --> 00:47:37.270
I'll gamble with sevens, ace,
jack, king, queen, ace 10

00:47:37.270 --> 00:47:37.950
suited.

00:47:37.950 --> 00:47:39.790
So we'll get around
the table and then

00:47:39.790 --> 00:47:44.000
the range will slowly increase.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:47.830
Also note that these are
very conservative ranges.

00:47:47.830 --> 00:47:51.380
If you watch high stakes
poker, probably the players

00:47:51.380 --> 00:47:54.520
will open a lot more hands than
what I'm recommending here.

00:47:54.520 --> 00:47:56.890
But my general
experience has been

00:47:56.890 --> 00:47:59.050
when you're just starting
out to play poker

00:47:59.050 --> 00:48:01.690
it's much easier to err
on the side of being

00:48:01.690 --> 00:48:04.140
too tight than being too loose.

00:48:04.140 --> 00:48:06.730
Because it's in some
sense a lot easier

00:48:06.730 --> 00:48:09.520
to play pocket aces
than seven five suited.

00:48:09.520 --> 00:48:11.020
With pocket aces
you're always going

00:48:11.020 --> 00:48:12.394
to have a pair of
aces or better.

00:48:12.394 --> 00:48:14.434
You just back that bet.

00:48:14.434 --> 00:48:15.850
And then with seven
five suite you

00:48:15.850 --> 00:48:18.160
need to be able to
bluff very carefully,

00:48:18.160 --> 00:48:21.406
you need to sometimes be able to
try to get value when you just

00:48:21.406 --> 00:48:22.280
hit a pair of sevens.

00:48:22.280 --> 00:48:24.190
And it's just a lot harder.

00:48:24.190 --> 00:48:26.740
So the ranges I'm
suggesting are very

00:48:26.740 --> 00:48:28.770
tight by most poker standards.

00:48:28.770 --> 00:48:30.700
By tight I mean conservative.

00:48:30.700 --> 00:48:32.290
But I think that's
the right side

00:48:32.290 --> 00:48:35.130
to err on when
you're just starting.

00:48:35.130 --> 00:48:38.230
So these are the ranges.

00:48:38.230 --> 00:48:40.580
As we get to the later
positions, so this is Low Jack,

00:48:40.580 --> 00:48:42.960
we're opening more hands now.

00:48:42.960 --> 00:48:44.440
Any two suited Broadways.

00:48:44.440 --> 00:48:47.010
So that's hands like jack
10 suited, queen 10 suited.

00:48:47.010 --> 00:48:48.400
It's basically
any two cards that

00:48:48.400 --> 00:48:52.281
are the same suit and
both 10 or higher.

00:48:52.281 --> 00:48:54.280
So maybe I should just
run through this quickly.

00:48:54.280 --> 00:48:57.532
So why is having your
cards be suited good?

00:48:57.532 --> 00:49:00.172
AUDIENCE: You get a flush.

00:49:00.172 --> 00:49:00.880
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:49:00.880 --> 00:49:03.005
So if it suited you're more
likely to make a flush.

00:49:03.005 --> 00:49:05.260
But if have two unsuited
cards then there's

00:49:05.260 --> 00:49:07.200
two different flushes
you could get.

00:49:09.800 --> 00:49:11.710
If you have queens or
diamonds, 10 of spades

00:49:11.710 --> 00:49:14.470
is going to make a diamond
flush or a spade flush.

00:49:14.470 --> 00:49:16.360
Essentially, that
argument is wrong

00:49:16.360 --> 00:49:18.280
because there's two
reasons why it's wrong.

00:49:18.280 --> 00:49:20.830
One is it's not more of a
play because you need four

00:49:20.830 --> 00:49:22.900
of the suit to make a flush.

00:49:22.900 --> 00:49:26.300
And two is, when you make the
flush it's also more obvious

00:49:26.300 --> 00:49:27.760
you have the flush.

00:49:27.760 --> 00:49:28.260
like

00:49:28.260 --> 00:49:29.980
If you only have
one diamond, even

00:49:29.980 --> 00:49:32.030
if it's the ace of
diamonds, once there's

00:49:32.030 --> 00:49:34.180
four diamonds on the
board it's way more likely

00:49:34.180 --> 00:49:35.099
that you have a flush.

00:49:35.099 --> 00:49:36.640
So you're going to
get paid off less.

00:49:36.640 --> 00:49:39.067
Whereas if you have two
diamonds in your hand

00:49:39.067 --> 00:49:40.900
and there's only three
diamonds on the board

00:49:40.900 --> 00:49:43.360
it's less susceptible
that you have a flush.

00:49:48.160 --> 00:49:50.920
So high jack is
three to the button.

00:49:50.920 --> 00:49:52.680
So this is what I
would recommend.

00:49:52.680 --> 00:49:57.530
So any pair, pairs
are pretty good.

00:49:57.530 --> 00:50:00.010
Any suited ace, so
suited ace means any card

00:50:00.010 --> 00:50:03.040
with any hand with an ace and
another card of the same suit.

00:50:03.040 --> 00:50:04.840
Any suited connector.

00:50:04.840 --> 00:50:08.020
By that I mean hands
like basically two cards

00:50:08.020 --> 00:50:11.900
that are next to each other and
also the same suit, like 10,

00:50:11.900 --> 00:50:12.400
9--

00:50:12.400 --> 00:50:13.960
10 of spades, nine of spades.

00:50:13.960 --> 00:50:17.320
Or any two unsuited
Broadway cards.

00:50:17.320 --> 00:50:20.000
So I do use a lot
of terminology here.

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:23.597
So yeah, please stop me
if something is unclear.

00:50:23.597 --> 00:50:25.180
You can google most
of these, I think.

00:50:33.509 --> 00:50:34.800
And suited connectors are good.

00:50:34.800 --> 00:50:36.910
So like a hand like
seven, six suited

00:50:36.910 --> 00:50:40.297
is often better than a
hand like 10, 6 suited,

00:50:40.297 --> 00:50:42.130
even though the trend
is bigger than the six

00:50:42.130 --> 00:50:44.485
because ten is sort of a
small enough card where

00:50:44.485 --> 00:50:47.020
it's not that relevant, the
fact that it's a big card.

00:50:47.020 --> 00:50:48.960
But the fact that
seven, six is connected

00:50:48.960 --> 00:50:52.774
and can hit a lot more
straights is very relevant.

00:50:52.774 --> 00:50:54.190
So we're if we're
cut off I'm just

00:50:54.190 --> 00:50:56.148
going to show you on
PokerStove because there's

00:50:56.148 --> 00:50:57.090
too many to list.

00:50:57.090 --> 00:50:59.620
But the thing I want you
to know is the percentages.

00:50:59.620 --> 00:51:01.130
30%.

00:51:01.130 --> 00:51:04.380
So remember, under the gun
I recommended playing 6%.

00:51:04.380 --> 00:51:08.070
So we've multiplied
how bad our hand could

00:51:08.070 --> 00:51:10.050
be for us to play by five.

00:51:10.050 --> 00:51:13.030
And I think this is what I
really want you to try to do.

00:51:13.030 --> 00:51:14.640
And I think what a
lot of new players

00:51:14.640 --> 00:51:17.181
don't do enough is they always
play the same cards regardless

00:51:17.181 --> 00:51:17.969
of their position.

00:51:17.969 --> 00:51:19.510
And then even crazier,
on the button,

00:51:19.510 --> 00:51:21.340
if everyone in
front of you folds,

00:51:21.340 --> 00:51:24.210
I recommend them playing
about 55% of hands.

00:51:24.210 --> 00:51:24.990
This is huge.

00:51:24.990 --> 00:51:27.540
I want you to play
jack three suited.

00:51:27.540 --> 00:51:30.110
Who thinks jack three
suited is a good hand?

00:51:30.110 --> 00:51:33.430
Or king four off-suit,
or queen six off-suit.

00:51:36.920 --> 00:51:38.670
What hands do we play
from the small blind

00:51:38.670 --> 00:51:40.920
if it's folded to you?

00:51:40.920 --> 00:51:44.070
So let's compare opening from
the small blind to opening

00:51:44.070 --> 00:51:44.757
from the button.

00:51:44.757 --> 00:51:46.590
So for small blind it's
a bit different now.

00:51:49.470 --> 00:51:51.840
So I should mention
this because when

00:51:51.840 --> 00:51:56.550
you're raising from the button,
from the dealer, if you get

00:51:56.550 --> 00:51:59.737
called you get to
act last post-flop.

00:51:59.737 --> 00:52:02.070
So I'm going to talk more
about this in future lectures.

00:52:02.070 --> 00:52:06.030
But this is basically called
having position post-flop.

00:52:06.030 --> 00:52:08.090
And having position
is basically good.

00:52:08.090 --> 00:52:08.637
Yeah.

00:52:08.637 --> 00:52:10.220
AUDIENCE: For all
these hands, are you

00:52:10.220 --> 00:52:12.140
assuming that everyone's
folding behind you?

00:52:12.140 --> 00:52:13.440
PROFESSOR: Yes, yes.

00:52:13.440 --> 00:52:16.117
If people haven't
folded, essentially, I'll

00:52:16.117 --> 00:52:17.700
talk more about this
in future classes

00:52:17.700 --> 00:52:20.130
but essentially what
you need to do if--

00:52:20.130 --> 00:52:24.480
so let let's say this guy
raised and you're the button.

00:52:24.480 --> 00:52:28.230
Essentially you need to
consider what his range is

00:52:28.230 --> 00:52:30.410
and calculate your equity
against his range, which

00:52:30.410 --> 00:52:30.910
you can do--

00:52:30.910 --> 00:52:32.620
AUDIENCE: The calculation
is completely different.

00:52:32.620 --> 00:52:33.260
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:52:33.260 --> 00:52:35.093
So the calculation is
essentially completely

00:52:35.093 --> 00:52:36.120
different.

00:52:36.120 --> 00:52:39.690
So essentially the
first guy who raised

00:52:39.690 --> 00:52:42.845
determines what the barrier
to entry to the pot is.

00:52:42.845 --> 00:52:44.220
Because essentially
the first guy

00:52:44.220 --> 00:52:47.340
that raises, if it's from under
the gun, he's telling you,

00:52:47.340 --> 00:52:49.234
my range is pocket eights plus.

00:52:49.234 --> 00:52:50.775
Even if he's sort
of loose it's still

00:52:50.775 --> 00:52:55.650
going to be pocket fours plus
and queen 10 suited plus.

00:52:55.650 --> 00:53:00.240
Basically it's saying, if you're
playing eight six suited then

00:53:00.240 --> 00:53:03.210
you're basically in
idiot, because my range is

00:53:03.210 --> 00:53:04.090
way better than that.

00:53:04.090 --> 00:53:07.140
So essentially the first guy
who plays this hand sort of

00:53:07.140 --> 00:53:10.820
sets the tone on how good
your hand needs to be.

00:53:17.049 --> 00:53:18.090
Thanks for that question.

00:53:18.090 --> 00:53:20.131
So I'll talk more about
this in a future lecture.

00:53:20.131 --> 00:53:24.120
But essentially that's
what you need to do.

00:53:24.120 --> 00:53:27.200
So from the small blind let's
compare opening the small blind

00:53:27.200 --> 00:53:28.830
from opening the button.

00:53:28.830 --> 00:53:30.970
So the issue with
opening the small blind

00:53:30.970 --> 00:53:32.671
is if the big blind
calls you actually

00:53:32.671 --> 00:53:33.920
don't have position post-flop.

00:53:33.920 --> 00:53:36.040
The big blind gets to
act after you post-flop.

00:53:36.040 --> 00:53:36.660
Pot.

00:53:36.660 --> 00:53:38.700
So it's actually a lot
worse in some sense

00:53:38.700 --> 00:53:40.366
than opening from the
button because you

00:53:40.366 --> 00:53:41.370
don't get you act last.

00:53:41.370 --> 00:53:44.530
But it is better in the sense
that there's one fewer person

00:53:44.530 --> 00:53:45.330
to get through.

00:53:45.330 --> 00:53:47.880
And also, you have less to
wager, which is actually

00:53:47.880 --> 00:53:51.510
really relevant because
from the button,

00:53:51.510 --> 00:53:57.910
if the blinds are 2,000 or 1,000
or OK, let's just dictate it.

00:53:57.910 --> 00:53:59.790
So if the blinds
are 20, 40, if you

00:53:59.790 --> 00:54:02.730
want to steal the lines from the
button and you want to do 2.25

00:54:02.730 --> 00:54:04.080
you need to put in 90.

00:54:04.080 --> 00:54:06.530
You raise me 90 and
you need to wager 90.

00:54:06.530 --> 00:54:08.280
But if you're raising
from the small blind

00:54:08.280 --> 00:54:10.500
you only need to put in 70 more.

00:54:10.500 --> 00:54:12.540
So you're actually
paying a smaller price

00:54:12.540 --> 00:54:14.414
to try to steal the blinds.

00:54:14.414 --> 00:54:16.080
But the fact that
you're out of position

00:54:16.080 --> 00:54:18.212
is a very important negative.

00:54:18.212 --> 00:54:19.920
So I'd say all these
factors balance out.

00:54:19.920 --> 00:54:22.140
And you can roughly play
the same range of hands

00:54:22.140 --> 00:54:24.570
from the small blind as you
would from the big blind.

00:54:24.570 --> 00:54:26.984
I think that's a
reasonable rule of thumb.

00:54:26.984 --> 00:54:28.650
But the fact that
you're out of position

00:54:28.650 --> 00:54:31.770
hurts a lot less as stacks
get shallower, essentially

00:54:31.770 --> 00:54:35.900
as effective stack
sizes get a lot smaller.

00:54:35.900 --> 00:54:39.200
So you could really
drastically increase this range

00:54:39.200 --> 00:54:42.726
if you only have 10 big
blinds from the small blind.

00:54:45.980 --> 00:54:48.050
So let me just give a
few caveats about this.

00:54:48.050 --> 00:54:49.675
So actually, I'll
leave it to you guys.

00:54:49.675 --> 00:54:51.620
If someone comes up with
a very good complaint

00:54:51.620 --> 00:54:53.810
