00:55:07.204 --> 00:55:07.870
PROFESSOR: Good.

00:55:07.870 --> 00:55:09.026
That's a very good point.

00:55:09.026 --> 00:55:11.150
A lot of people ask me,
why would you follow these?

00:55:11.150 --> 00:55:13.310
If I follow these everyone
knows what I'm doing.

00:55:13.310 --> 00:55:19.690
Well the point is, for most
of these, even this range,

00:55:19.690 --> 00:55:21.950
it sort of encompasses
enough hands.

00:55:21.950 --> 00:55:25.280
So this is where I'm talking
about optimal balance play.

00:55:25.280 --> 00:55:28.100
I think even though humans
haven't solved poker,

00:55:28.100 --> 00:55:31.100
I think roughly,
if you want to ask,

00:55:31.100 --> 00:55:34.720
I would guess that roughly
the optimal range of hands

00:55:34.720 --> 00:55:36.851
you open from this position
is something like this.

00:55:36.851 --> 00:55:37.850
It's going to be looser.

00:55:37.850 --> 00:55:39.920
But it's something
roughly like this.

00:55:39.920 --> 00:55:44.180
Probably you want to
probabilistic play some smaller

00:55:44.180 --> 00:55:46.980
cards just so when the
flop comes 2, 2, 4,

00:55:46.980 --> 00:55:48.382
you can potentially have a two.

00:55:48.382 --> 00:55:50.090
But essentially you're
not doing bad here

00:55:50.090 --> 00:55:53.712
because if the flop comes
three small cards then

00:55:53.712 --> 00:55:55.670
you were going to be
doing pretty well with all

00:55:55.670 --> 00:55:56.930
your big pairs.

00:55:56.930 --> 00:55:58.940
And if the flop
comes the big cards

00:55:58.940 --> 00:56:04.630
you've still got ace king, ace
queen, ace jack in your hand.

00:56:04.630 --> 00:56:10.520
But not that is
a good complaint.

00:56:10.520 --> 00:56:13.450
So in theory, it's
in theory optimal

00:56:13.450 --> 00:56:16.630
to play seven seven some
fraction of the time,

00:56:16.630 --> 00:56:18.330
six six some
fraction of the time,

00:56:18.330 --> 00:56:20.060
and two two some
fraction of the time.

00:56:20.060 --> 00:56:23.286
But that's making things
really complicated.

00:56:23.286 --> 00:56:24.910
I don't want to add
two two to the list

00:56:24.910 --> 00:56:26.900
because if you play two
two every single time

00:56:26.900 --> 00:56:28.070
then that's way too loose.

00:56:28.070 --> 00:56:30.440
You're just spewing money
by raising with two two

00:56:30.440 --> 00:56:32.810
against this many
players behind.

00:56:32.810 --> 00:56:34.580
So ideally maybe
with two twos you

00:56:34.580 --> 00:56:37.242
should do a random
number generator and 10%

00:56:37.242 --> 00:56:38.450
of the time you play two two.

00:56:38.450 --> 00:56:40.870
That would probably be
theoretically optimal.

00:56:40.870 --> 00:56:42.594
OK, good.

00:56:42.594 --> 00:56:43.760
That would have gotten this.

00:56:43.760 --> 00:56:44.800
But OK, I'll give it to--

00:56:44.800 --> 00:56:45.274
Yeah.

00:56:45.274 --> 00:56:47.482
AUDIENCE: I think another
problem with playing really

00:56:47.482 --> 00:56:50.070
tight all the time is that
